{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_019SZrwd7inKBXSc5jtWe9b7","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me work through each behavior systematically, using the key questions provided to determine the minimum test level needed.\n\nFor each behavior, I need to think:\n1. Could mocking hide this failure? (MOCK-MISS)\n2. Does it depend on OS, network, subprocess? (REAL-INFRA)\n3. Would mocking this dependency always pass? (MOCK-HIDE)\n4. Does it depend on real LLM output? (LLM-DEP)\n5. Multiple agentic steps? (MULTI-STEP)\n\nLet me go through each:\n\n---\n\n**Behavior 1: Required patient fields validation**\n\nDescription: Required patient fields (name, date of birth, insurance ID) are validated before any downstream processing — missing fields produce a clear error listing all missing items.\n\nAnalysis:\n- This is pure in-process validation logic\n- No external API calls needed\n- No DB writes yet (validation happens before downstream)\n- No LLM involved\n- The test is: pass incomplete input, verify error message lists all missing fields\n- Could be caught by a simple unit test with mocked downstream dependencies\n- No mock would hide this — it's synchronous validation\n\n**Minimum level: Unit**\n\nThe test only needs to verify that the validation function/endpoint rejects incomplete input and returns a formatted error. This happens locally, deterministically.\n\n**Level probabilities:**\n- Unit: 0.85 (this is pure validation logic)\n- Integration: 0.10 (could argue we need real request parsing, but typically not)\n- System: 0.05 (unlikely to be OS-dependent)\n- Agentic: 0.0\n- Workflow: 0.0\n\nActually, let me reconsider. Could there be a real failure that a unit test would miss?\n- HTTP parsing issues? Could be real if the API accepts malformed JSON\n- Framework-level validation that strips fields differently?\n- Ordering of validation messages?\n\nStill, the core behavior (field presence check) is unit-level. The test should verify that:\n\n\n- All three fields are checked\n- Missing fields are reported in the error\n- The error message is clear\n\nThis is Unit. Very confident.\n\n---\n\n**Behavior 2: Date of birth validation**\n\nDescription: Date of birth validation rejects future dates, dates more than 150 years ago, and non-date strings.\n\nAnalysis:\n- Pure validation logic, no external calls\n- Three boundary conditions to test\n- Could be caught by unit test\n- No mocking would hide this\n\n**Minimum level: Unit**\n\nThe test validates date parsing and boundary checking. All conditions are deterministic.\n\n**Level probabilities:**\n- Unit: 0.90\n- Integration: 0.05\n- System: 0.05\n- Agentic: 0\n\n.0\n- Workflow: 0.0\n\n---\n\n**Behavior 3: Insurance eligibility check**\n\nDescription: The insurance eligibility check sends the correct patient ID and plan code to the payer API and correctly interprets the \"eligible\" vs \"not eligible\" vs \"pending\" response.\n\nAnalysis:\n- External payer API call required\n- Must verify correct parameters are sent\n- Must verify correct interpretation of responses\n- A mock could always return \"eligible,\" but the real API might have malformed responses, unexpected status codes, missing headers, or other issues that only surface against actual infrastructure\n- Real network behavior matters here—latency, timeouts, TLS validation, and rate limiting could all affect how the system handles responses\n- Getting response parsing wrong would only be caught against the real API\n\nFor testing \"correct request format and response parsing,\" I don't need the actual payer API. I can use an integration test with a mock HTTP server (responses library, httpretty) to verify request structure (headers, body, method) and response parsing for each case (eligible, not eligible, pending). This catches serialization bugs, wrong HTTP methods, missing headers, and parsing errors without hitting real infrastructure.\n\n**Minimum level: Integration**\n\nA pure unit test with a mocked HTTP client wouldn't catch serialization issues, incorrect HTTP methods, missing headers, or response parsing bugs. An integration test with a mock HTTP server is sufficient—no need for System-level testing against the real payer API.\n\n**Level probabilities:**\n- Unit: 0.05 (pure mock wouldn't catch serialization/parsing bugs)\n- Integration: 0.85 (mock HTTP server can verify request/response)\n- System: 0.10 (could argue need real API call for full confidence)\n- Agentic: 0.0\n- Workflow: 0.0\n\n---\n\n**Behavior 4: Payer API unreachable**\n\nDescription: When the payer API is unreachable, the system marks eligibility as \"pending\" and continues the intake rather than blocking.\n\nAnalysis:\n- Tests failure handling when external API is down\n- Need to verify the system doesn't block, doesn't crash\n- Need to verify \"pending\" state is set\n- Could use Integration level with mocked HTTP error\n- Or System level to test real network timeout/failure\n\nKey question: Could mocking miss this?\n- A mock could always be \"reachable\", so testing the happy path wouldn't expose whether the system properly handles unavailability. I need to simulate actual network failures—either through integration-level error injection or system-level testing against real infrastructure to ensure the fallback behavior works correctly.\n\n**Minimum level: Integration**\n\nMocking the HTTP client to throw exceptions lets me verify the system degrades gracefully without needing a real API. The error handling logic itself doesn't require production infrastructure.\n\n**Level probabilities:**\n- Unit: 0.10\n- Integration: 0.85\n- System: 0.05\n- Agentic: 0.0\n- Workflow: 0.0\n\n---\n\n**Behavior 5: AI symptom triage — high urgency for emergency conditions**\n\nDescription: The AI symptom triage correctly assigns high urgency to symptom combinations that indicate emergency conditions (e.g., chest pain + shortness of breath).\n\nAnalysis:\n- Depends on real AI/ML model to classify symptoms\n- The model must actually receive the input and produce a classification\n- Key question: LLM-DEP?\n  - YES. The correctness depends on what the real AI medical reasoning engine produces\n  - An LLM could hallucinate, miss the condition, or classify incorrectly\n  - Results might vary across runs depending on temperature and model version\n\n**Minimum level: Agentic**\n\nI can't verify the model identifies emergency conditions without invoking the actual model or a high-fidelity mock trained on real data. A simple mock that always returns \"high urgency\" would pass the test but wouldn't validate the model's actual reasoning. Testing this requires calling the real model with chest pain + shortness of breath and checking for high urgency classification, though results could be flaky if temperature settings are high.\n\n**Level probabilities:**\n- Unit: 0.0\n- Integration: 0.05\n- System: 0.05\n- Agentic: 0.85 (real model call required)\n- Workflow: 0.05\n\n---\n\n**Behavior 6: Symptom triage produces natural language explanation**\n\nDescription: The symptom triage produces a natural language explanation of its urgency assessment that a clinician can review, not just a numeric score.\n\nAnalysis:\n- Depends on real AI model output\n- The model must generate text (natural language explanation)\n- Key question: LLM-DEP?\n  - YES. Whether the explanation is clear, accurate, and helpful depends on the real model\n  - A mock could always return \"chest pain indicates high urgency\" but the real model might return \"patient experiencing cardiac distress\"\n\n**Minimum level: Agentic**\n\nThe real model is necessary to verify it produces an explanation rather than just a score. A mock could be configured to always return an explanation, but that wouldn't confirm the actual model does. Testing requires the real model to validate the quality and format of generated explanations.\n\n**Level probabilities:**\n- Unit: 0.0\n- Integration: 0.05\n- System: 0.05\n- Agentic: 0.85\n- Workflow: 0.05\n\n---\n\n**Behavior 7: Appointment scheduling — urgency-based slots\n\nDescription: An appointment is scheduled in the first available slot that matches the assigned urgency level — high urgency gets same-day, medium gets within 48 hours.\n\nAnalysis:\n- Involves database writes to a calendar\n- Must verify correct slot selection based on urgency\n- No LLM needed (logic, not AI)\n- Key question: MOCK-MISS?\n  - Could mocking the calendar DB miss this?\n  - A mock could always have slots available, but real calendar might have no same-day slots\n  - However, the test is about the algorithm: \"given slots X, Y, Z, select the right one\"\n  - This is testable with mocked calendar data\n\n**Minimum level: Integration**\n\nI can test this with a fake calendar database containing predefined slots. The test verifies the algorithm selects the correct slot based on urgency level—whether high urgency gets same-day appointments or medium urgency gets 48-hour slots. A mock database is sufficient since the core logic is about slot selection, not real calendar availability.\n\n**Level probabilities:**\n- Unit: 0.0\n- Integration: 0.85\n- System: 0.1\n- Agentic: 0.0\n- Workflow: 0.05\n\n---\n\n**Behavior 8: No double-booking with concurrent processing**\n\nDescription: The scheduling step does not double-book a time slot even when two patients are being processed concurrently.\n\nAnalysis:\n- Concurrency issue: two processes trying to book the same slot simultaneously\n- Requires real database and transaction handling OR a simulation of concurrent access\n- Key question: REAL-INFRA?\n  - YES. Race conditions are OS-level concurrency issues\n  - A mock in-process database might use locks that prevent race conditions\n  - Real database transactions might fail or have different isolation levels\n  - Need to test actual concurrency behavior\n\nThis requires testing actual concurrent access patterns, not just mocked sequential behavior.\n\nCould use threading to simulate concurrent requests against a real in-memory database like SQLite, which would properly handle transaction isolation and locking. Alternatively, running against the production database with concurrent requests would verify the actual behavior, but that's overkill for this scenario.\n\n**Minimum level: Integration** — need real concurrency and transaction handling, but an in-memory test database suffices. System-level testing would only be necessary if production-specific database behavior needs verification.\n\n---\n\n**Behavior 9: Confirmation message includes correct details**\n\nDescription: The confirmation message includes the patient name, appointment time, provider name, and preparation instructions appropriate to the visit type.\n\nAnalysis:\n- Template rendering / message composition\n- No external API calls (might send email/SMS, but focus is on message content)\n- No LLM needed (structured message)\n- Could be caught by unit test with mocked downstream services (email, SMS)\n\n**Minimum level: Unit**\n\nThe test:\n- Create test patient data\n- Mock appointment scheduling result\n- Verify confirmation message contains all required fields\n- Possibly mock email/SMS service\n\nNo external infra needed.\n\n**Level probabilities:**\n- Unit: 0.90\n- Integration: 0.05\n- System: 0.05\n- Agentic: 0.0\n- Workflow: 0.0\n\n---\n\n**Behavior 10: Full intake pipeline**\n\nDescription: The full intake pipeline — validate, check insurance, triage symptoms, schedule, confirm — completes for a real patient submission without manual intervention.\n\nAnalysis:\n- Multiple steps in sequence\n- Includes agentic step (symptom triage with AI model)\n- Includes external API call (insurance check)\n- Includes database write (scheduling)\n- Includes message generation (confirmation)\n\nKey question: MULTI-STEP?\n- YES. This is a full end-to-end workflow orchestrating validation, insurance verification, AI-driven triage, appointment scheduling, and confirmation messaging. Each step depends on the previous one succeeding, and failures at any stage should prevent progression.\n\nThe limiting factor is the agentic component (AI triage), but the real challenge is testing the orchestration itself—error handling between steps, state passing, and recovery. For instance, if insurance verification returns \"pending\" status, does the pipeline continue appropriately? If AI triage is slow, does the scheduling step timeout? These cross-step interactions are what define this as Workflow-level.\n\n**Level probabilities:**\n- Unit: 0.0\n- Integration: 0.0\n- System: 0.05\n- Agentic: 0.10\n- Workflow: 0.85\n\n---\n\nReconsidering the minimum infrastructure question: what's the bare minimum needed to catch a real failure, not just verify happy-path logic? For behaviors 5 & 6 (AI triage), I could mock the AI model with deterministic responses—always returning specific urgency levels for known inputs—and verify the intake system correctly passes data and uses results. But that approach risks missing actual failures: broken API calls to the AI service, incorrect response parsing, or malformed data handling.\n\nBehavior 7 (scheduling) depends on whether the logic is pure or involves database queries. If it's just an algorithm selecting from available slots, Unit testing works. But if it queries the database to find available slots and check existing bookings, Integration is needed.\n\nBehavior 8 (concurrency) requires at least Integration-level testing with real concurrent operations, possibly System-level if production database behavior differs.\n\nBehavior 10 (full pipeline) is clearly Workflow because multiple agentic and system steps must coordinate, with error handling and state passing across the entire sequence.\n\nNow I should verify whether each test actually requires the level I've assigned, or if it could pass at a lower level. For instance, a Unit test checking that a missing name field produces an error would pass at Unit level. An Agentic test verifying the AI model returns high urgency for chest pain with shortness of breath genuinely needs the real model. I need to reconsider Behavior 3 more carefully—it involves both sending the correct request to the payer API and interpreting the response correctly, which are distinct concerns.\n\nFor the request/response handling itself, I can use an Integration test with a mocked HTTP server to verify the patient ID and plan code are sent correctly and that the three response types (eligible, not eligible, pending) are parsed properly. System-level testing would be needed to catch authentication issues, actual API format variations, or rate limiting, but basic correctness doesn't require hitting the real API. Since the definition distinguishes between mocked HTTP responses and real external API calls, Behavior 3 stays at Integration.\n\nNow for test descriptions—these should capture what's actually being verified rather than restating the behavior. For required field validation, I'm checking that missing any of name, DOB, or insurance ID triggers an error listing all missing fields. DOB validation needs to reject future dates, dates over 150 years old, and invalid date strings while accepting legitimate dates. The insurance API interaction verifies correct transmission of patient ID and plan code plus proper parsing of the three response states. When the API fails—whether through HTTP errors, timeouts, or exceptions—the system should default eligibility to pending and proceed. For AI triage, high urgency assignment needs to work correctly for specific symptom combinations like chest pain with shortness of breath.\n\nThe AI explanation test confirms the model generates natural language reasoning rather than just outputting a numeric score. Slot selection logic should prioritize same-day availability for high urgency cases and within-48-hour windows for medium urgency. Concurrent scheduling requires that only one patient successfully books when two requests target the same slot simultaneously. Confirmation messages must include patient name, appointment time, provider name, and relevant preparation guidance. Finally, the end-to-end test validates the complete flow from validation through insurance checks, triage assessment, scheduling, and confirmation for an actual patient submission.\n\nFor the JSON output, I'm mapping each behavior to its appropriate test level with probabilities. Starting with required field validation: this is straightforward synchronous logic that can be tested in isolation by passing incomplete patient records and checking that error messages enumerate exactly which fields are missing. Unit testing suffices here since no external service mocking would obscure whether the validation correctly identifies missing data. The probability distribution heavily favors Unit (0.90) with minimal likelihood of higher levels.\n\nDate of birth validation follows similar reasoning—it's deterministic boundary checking that doesn't require integration or system-level concerns. Testing can directly invoke the validation function with edge cases like future dates, dates exceeding 150 years in the past, and malformed strings to confirm proper rejection. Again, Unit dominates the probability distribution.\n\nFor the insurance API interaction, this shifts to Integration level since it involves external service communication.\n\nThe test needs to verify HTTP request serialization—ensuring patient ID and plan code are in the correct fields with proper JSON structure and headers—plus response parsing for three distinct outcomes (eligible, not eligible, pending). A unit test with mocks can't catch serialization bugs like wrong field names or malformed requests. Using a mocked HTTP server (responses library, httpretty) lets us validate the full request/response cycle without calling the actual API. The test should confirm the request payload matches expectations and each response type gets parsed correctly into the appropriate state.\n\nSystem-level testing isn't necessary here because we don't need the real API to verify request formatting and response handling—a mock server covers all valid and error responses. System testing would be relevant for authentication, TLS validation, or rate limiting, which are secondary concerns. Integration testing captures the core behavior: correct request structure and proper interpretation of responses. While one could argue the real API might expose undocumented response formats or timeout behaviors, the essential functionality is testable at the Integration level.\n\nFor API unreachability, the test must simulate failure conditions—connection errors, timeouts, 5XX responses—and confirm the system handles these gracefully by marking eligibility as pending and continuing intake without crashing. This is achievable at Integration level by mocking the HTTP layer to throw exceptions or return errors; a unit test with all-succeeding mocks would miss the failure handling logic entirely. The test mocks the HTTP client to raise ConnectionError, TimeoutError, and 5XX responses, verifying each results in eligibility='pending' and unblocked intake.\n\nFor AI triage and emergency symptom detection, the minimum level is Agentic because correctness depends on the actual AI model's reasoning. A mock that always returns 'high urgency' for chest pain would pass unit tests but wouldn't validate the real model's behavior.  The actual model may misclassify, hallucinate, or vary based on temperature and version. Testing requires calling the real model with known emergency combinations like chest pain plus shortness of breath, running 5-10 cases to verify high urgency classification across the board.\n\nFor the explanation output, the real model's ability to generate clinician-readable text alongside urgency scores is also model-dependent. A mock could trivially return explanation strings, but the actual implementation might only provide numeric scores or produce unhelpful text. Verifying this requires testing against the real system with actual symptom inputs, checking that the response includes a non-empty explanation field with contextual details—mentioning specific symptoms or medical reasoning rather than generic boilerplate. Both behaviors demand agentic-level testing since only the real model can confirm these outputs actually occur.\n\nFor appointment scheduling, the system needs to verify that slots are selected correctly based on urgency tiers—same-day for high priority, within 48 hours for medium. This requires either a real or mocked calendar database with predefined available slots, then confirming the algorithm picks the right one for each urgency level. If scheduling is purely functional logic, unit testing could work, but since it typically involves database lookups to find available slots within specific timeframes, integration testing is more appropriate.\n\nThe test would set up a calendar with slots across different time windows, call the scheduling function with various urgency levels, and verify the correct slot is selected—high urgency gets same-day, medium gets within the 48-hour window, and the earliest available slot is chosen.\n\nConcurrency presents a different challenge. When two patients attempt to book the same slot simultaneously, the system must prevent double-booking through proper transaction handling and database locks. This goes beyond what an in-memory mock can reliably test, since mocks typically lack real locking mechanisms that would catch race conditions.\n\nAn Integration test using a transactional test database like SQLite or in-memory Postgres can validate this behavior without needing production infrastructure. The test spawns two concurrent requests targeting the same 2pm slot with different patient IDs, then verifies exactly one succeeds while the other fails, and confirms the slot isn't double-booked in the database. System-level testing would only be necessary if the production database exhibits isolation issues that the test database doesn't replicate.\n\nThe System possibility exists because production databases might use different isolation levels (READ_UNCOMMITTED versus SERIALIZABLE), which could cause race conditions to behave differently than in testing environments. However, a properly configured Integration test with transaction handling typically suffices.\n\nFor confirmation message completeness, I'm checking whether the message includes patient name, appointment time, provider name, and preparation instructions specific to the visit type. This is deterministic template rendering given fixed inputs—no external API calls or delivery mechanisms involved. A unit test can mock the appointment data and patient record, then verify all required fields appear in the generated message. System: 0.08\n  - Agentic: 0.15\n  - Workflow: 0.75\n\nThis behavior demands Workflow-level testing because the pipeline orchestration itself is critical—error handling between steps, state management, and cascading failures all matter. If the insurance API times out, downstream scheduling could fail silently. The agentic symptom triage is the weakest link, so testing only at that level would miss orchestration gaps. The test needs to run the full sequence with real models, real (or stubbed) external APIs, and persistent storage, then verify all five steps complete: patient record created, insurance eligibility determined, triage urgency assigned with reasoning, appointment booked in an available slot, and confirmation sent. I'd also test failure modes—missing optional fields, API timeouts, no same-day availability—to ensure graceful degradation throughout the pipeline.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13505,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13505},"output_tokens":3,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"cc4f4306-d568-4cb7-9065-48d83399c27e","uuid":"7e1647db-5cfd-4a95-b8ed-885edef5c358"}
